<p>I read a story on Apple News this morning, <a href="https://apple.news/AE4TN3D2aSP6aZWNlDTJdKg">Northern lights may be viewable in some US states this week: Where and when to see it</a>, and I want to complain about it. Unlike my previous two posts, this will be short.</p>
<p>The article is from <em>USA Today</em>, and you can read it <a href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2025/04/15/northern-lights-forecast-aurora-borealis-states/83098515007/">on their site</a> in your browser, which you may prefer, as that gives you the opportunity to skip the ads via Reader Mode. But my complaint isn‚Äôt about ads in Apple News, it‚Äôs about the article itself.</p>
<p>You might think from the article‚Äôs title that its main topic is where you‚Äôll be able to see tonight‚Äôs northern lights. And it does get to that, but only after 400 words in a 600-word article, a frustrating inversion of the <a href="https://owl.purdue.edu/owl/subject_specific_writing/journalism_and_journalistic_writing/the_inverted_pyramid.html">inverted pyramid</a>. The 400 words of throat clearing explains what the northern lights are, what causes them, that they‚Äôre also called the <em>aurora borealis</em>, that there‚Äôs a similar phenomenon in the southern hemisphere called the <em>aurora australis</em>, and how NASA uses satellites to predict aurorae. These are all useful bits of information to people who don‚Äôt already know them, but they don‚Äôt belong before the list of states where you have a decent chance of seeing the northern lights.</p>
<p>(In some ways, of course, this <em>is</em> a complaint about ads. The inverted inverted pyramid structure is there to force you to scroll through the ads that Apple and USA Today want you to see.)</p>
<p>BBEdit says I‚Äôm now about 250 words into this post, so let me give you the list of states:</p>
<ul>
<li>North Dakota</li>
<li>Montana</li>
<li>Minnesota</li>
<li>Washington</li>
